SEARCH
Module org.klojang.jdbc
Package org.klojang.jdbc

Class BeanExtractorFactory<T>

java.lang.Object
org.klojang.jdbc.BeanExtractorFactory<T>
Type Parameters:
T - the type of JavaBeans or records produced by the extractor
All Implemented Interfaces:
ExtractorFactory<T>
public final class BeanExtractorFactory<T> extends Object implements ExtractorFactory<T>

A factory for BeanExtractor instances. Generally you would create one BeanExtractorFactory per SQL query. If multiple types of beans are extracted from the query result (different columns feeding into different types of beans), you would create more than one BeanExtractorFactory per SQL query. The very first ResultSet passed to BeanExtractorFactory.getExtractor() is used to configure the extraction process. ResultSet objects subsequently passed to getExtractor() will be processed identically. Therefore, passing a ResultSet that came from a completely different query will almost certainly lead to unexpected outcomes or exceptions.

The configuration of the extraction process may be somewhat expensive. Therefore it is recommended that you store BeanExtractorFactory instances in static final fields or use some sort of caching mechanism.

Author:
Ayco Holleman

    • BeanExtractorFactory

      public BeanExtractorFactory(FallibleFunction<ResultSet,T,SQLException> converter)
      Creates a new BeanExtractorFactory. BeanExtractor instances retrieved from this BeanExtractorFactory will use the provided conversion function to convert ResultSet rows into objects of type <T>. Contrary to the other constructors, using this one to instantiate a BeanExtractorFactory is cheap. Therefore, contrary to the recommendation in the class comments, there is no need to cache instances created this way, or store them in a static final field. Just create them when you need them.
      Parameters:
      converter - the row-to-bean conversion function
